
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `colcrt` baraye hazf underline-ha va nim-fasele-ha (half-lines) az khorooji estefade mishavad. Bishtar baraye matn-haye ASCII ke ba dastoor-haye digar sakhte shode ast (masalan, `man`), va underline baraye bold kardan ya chiz-haye digar estefade shode ast, be kar miravad.  Dar vaghe khorooji ra sade tar mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `colcrt -`  --> 🚫 Hame underline-ha ra bardar, hata underline-haye chand-taee.
    🔹 `colcrt -2` --> 📄 Fasele bayn khat-ha ra 2 barabar kon. Baraye chap kardane matn be soorate behtar ast.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ man ls | colcrt > ls.txt

    🔹 In dastoor khorooji `man ls` ra az tarighe `colcrt` rad mikonad ta underline-ha ra hazf konad va dar file `ls.txt` zakhire konad.

    $ colcrt - < file.txt

    🔹 In dastoor file `file.txt` ra mikhonad, underline-ha ra hazf mikonad, va khorooji ra dar terminal chap mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ man ls | colcrt | less

    🔹 In mesal underline-ha ra az khorooji `man ls` hazf mikonad va natije ra ba `less` namayesh midahad ta asan tar khande shavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `colcrt` command is used to filter out underline characters and half-lines from the input. It's primarily useful for processing ASCII text generated by other commands (like `man`) where underlines are used for bolding or other formatting. It simplifies the output.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `colcrt -`  --> 🚫 Suppress all underlining; multi-character sequences are treated correctly.
    🔹 `colcrt -2` --> 📄 Double space the output. This can be useful when printing for increased readability.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ man ls | colcrt > ls.txt

    🔹 This command pipes the output of `man ls` through `colcrt` to remove underlines and then saves the cleaned output to a file named `ls.txt`.

    $ colcrt - < file.txt

    🔹 This command reads `file.txt`, removes underlines, and prints the result to the terminal.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ man ls | colcrt | less

    🔹 This example removes underlines from the output of `man ls` and then displays the result using `less` for easier reading.
